[3] India - 2 suspected cases
Date: Wed 22 Feb 2006
From: Joe Dudley <jdudley@eaicorp.com>
Source: The Bangkok Post online, Wed 22 Feb 2006 [edited]
<http://www.bangkokpost.com/breaking_news/breakingnews.php?id=81097>

India Confirms Bird Flu in Humans
---------------------------------
Tests have confirmed the presence of the deadly H5N1 strain of avian
influenza virus in 2 blood samples taken from humans in India's
Maharashtra state, NDTV television network reported on Wednesday [22
Feb 2006].
Samples from 12 people suffering from mild respiratory disorders in
Nandurabr district in Maharashtra had been sent for testing, along
with samples from 90 people who had come into direct contact with
chickens in the infected zone. The 1st cases of H5N1 in chickens were
reported from poultry farms in Nandurbar, about 450 km north of the
Maharashtrian capital Mumbai, on Saturday [18 Feb 2006].
Initial test results indicated that 2 people were suffering from a
"mild version" of bird flu, that is, they were not showing all
typical symptoms of the full-blown version of the disease, NDTV
reported, citing sources in India's Health Ministry. The news channel
said an official announcement would be made later Wednesday [22 Feb
2006] or on Thursday morning. The tests are being conducted at the
National Institute of Virology in the Maharashtrian town of Pune and
the National Institute of Communicable Diseases in New Delhi. "The
possibility of the virus traveling to humans [transmitting from
person-to-person?] is a distinct possibility and cannot be ruled
out," Federal Health Secretary PK Hota said. He said the situation
should be taken seriously.
There have been no deaths from the virus yet in India. The 12 people
under observation at the district hospital in Navapur, the main town
in Nandurbar, are being kept in isolation, a Health Ministry release
said. The patients showed mild upper respiratory tract infection, and
their chest X-rays were normal, the release added.
Health authorities were continuing their house-to-house surveillance
in the infected zone to identify suspected cases among those exposed
to the infected poultry. The health of workers and officials involved
in the culling of chickens in the infected zone was also being
monitored, the Health Ministry said.
The federal Health Ministry said it had 50 000 courses of the
anti-flu drug Tamiflu in stock. Another 20 000 courses had been
ordered and were expected by Thursday [23 Feb 2006].
--
Joe Dudley
<jdudley@eaicorp.com>
[Until the 2 Indian cases have been verified by an external
WHO-approved laboratory, they remain classified as "suspected" cases
of avian influenza virus infection. The mildness of the illness in
the 2 suspected cases is an unusual feature. - Mod.CP]
