[4] Malaysia - suspected cases test negative
Date: Wed 22 Feb 2006
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Foundation AlertNet, Wed 22 Feb 2008 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/SP338871.htm>

Malaysia: 5 suspected Patients Test Negative
--------------------------------------------
Bird flu tests showed negative for 5 of the 7 people Malaysia
admitted to hospital on Wednesday [15 or 22 Feb 2006?] with breathing
problems, following its 1st poultry infection in over a year, the
Bernama News Agency reported. Health Minister Chua Soi Lek said tests
on 5 of the group exposed to sick chickens had turned out negative
for the deadly H5N1 virus, the state-run agency reported. Authorities
are still waiting for test results on the remaining 2, both children.
No human cases have so far been reported in Malaysia, which last
reported the H5N1 virus in a chicken in the northern state of
Kelantan in 2004.
Earlier, Chua said 2 adults and 5 children staying within 300 meters
(1000 feet) of the outbreak site were in hospital. "I will not say
that they were suspected," Chua told a news conference when asked
whether the 7 might have bird flu. "I would say that we are admitting
them for investigation to be on the safe side, because if they later
came out to be [confirmed cases] and they have been moving around
town, then it's not safe." Chua said the case was a "very isolated"
incident.
Chua has said the authorities had screened 916 people from 161 homes,
but only 7 people with respiratory tract infections had been admitted
to hospital.
[Byline: Syed Azman, with additional reporting by Jalil Hamid,
Clarence Fernandez and Barani Krishnan]
